  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "Similarly, S j denotes the jth sensing utility function with the threshold s j. M and J refer to the number of communication-and sensing-related constraints, respectively.From the perspective of target detection, the widely used utility functions are beam pattern mismatch [109][110][111], detection signal-to-interference-plus-noise ratio (SINR) [112][113][114][115][116], detection probability [117][118][119][120], CRB [121][122][123][124], and mutual information detection [125][126][127].",
    "For example, Hua et al. [109] minimized the mismatch between the optimized beam pattern and the ideal one subject to the power constraint and the SINR constraint at each user.",
    "Since the target detection probability is proportional to the acquisition SINR, Zhu et al. [112] maximized the acquisition SINR while satisfying the communication quality of service (QoS) constraint.",
    "Instead of maximizing the target detection probability in an indirect manner, Ren et al. [119] maximized the target detection probability directly and developed an effective algorithm to deal with this intractable non-convex optimization problem.",
    "The Bayesian CRB was minimized by Su et al. [124] subject to the QoS constraint of each user."
  ],
